<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>DHEA-S: The Hormonal Biomarker of Biological Age</h2>

  <p>Among the dozens of measurable hormones in the human body, DHEA-S stands out for one remarkable property: it declines with extraordinary consistency across the adult lifespan. Starting from peak levels around age 25, DHEA-S falls approximately 2–5% per year in both men and women — independent of health status, lifestyle, or most other variables. By age 70–80, most people have DHEA-S levels that are 80–90% lower than their youthful peak.</p>

  <p>This predictable trajectory has made DHEA-S one of the most studied biomarkers of biological aging. When a person's DHEA-S is significantly above or below the expected level for their chronological age, it provides meaningful signal about their pace of biological aging. People who maintain relatively higher DHEA-S levels into older age consistently demonstrate better health outcomes across multiple dimensions.</p>

  <p>A landmark analysis of the Baltimore Longitudinal Study of Aging found that men with the highest DHEA-S levels had significantly lower all-cause mortality over a follow-up period of 12 years, independent of other risk factors. The association between low DHEA-S and mortality has been replicated in multiple large prospective cohorts. <sup><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/3565999/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">1</a></sup></p>
</section>

<section class="bm-section">
  <h2>What DHEA-S Does and Why Levels Matter</h2>

  <p>DHEA-S functions primarily as a reservoir and precursor — a molecular bank from which peripheral tissues can draw to synthesize androgens and estrogens locally as needed. This "intracrinology" means DHEA-S supports hormonal function throughout the body in a more distributed, tissue-specific way than circulating testosterone or estradiol alone.</p>

  <p>Beyond its role as a hormone precursor, DHEA has direct biological effects including anti-inflammatory properties (it counters several pro-inflammatory cytokines), immunomodulatory effects (supporting NK cell activity and T-cell function), neuroprotective properties (DHEA receptors are found throughout the brain, and DHEA appears to protect neurons from excitotoxicity and oxidative stress), and direct effects on insulin sensitivity.</p>

